[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Some languages have automatic memoization built in, such as tabled Prolog and J, which supports memoization with the *M.* adverb.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] In any case, this is only possible for a referentially transparent function.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Memoization is also encountered as an easily accessible design pattern within term-rewrite based languages such as Wolfram Language.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming is widely used in bioinformatics for tasks such as sequence alignment, protein folding, RNA structure prediction and protein-DNA binding.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The first dynamic programming algorithms for protein-DNA binding were developed in the 1970s independently by Charles DeLisi in the US and by Georgii Gurskii and Alexander Zasedatelev in the Soviet Union.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Recently these algorithms have become very popular in bioinformatics and computational biology, particularly in the studies of nucleosome positioning and transcription factor binding.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm for the shortest path problem is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's famous Principle of Optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Using dynamic programming in the calculation of the *n*th member of the Fibonacci sequence improves its performance greatly.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] In particular, `fib(2)` was calculated three times from scratch.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] In larger examples, many more values of `fib`, or *subproblems*, are recalculated, leading to an exponential time algorithm.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Now, suppose we have a simple map object, *m*, which maps each value of `fib` that has already been calculated to its result, and we modify our function to use it and update it.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This technique of saving values that have already been calculated is called *memoization*; this is the top-down approach, since we first break the problem into subproblems and then calculate and store values.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] In the **bottom-up** approach, we calculate the smaller values of `fib` first, then build larger values from them.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This method also uses O(*n*) time since it contains a loop that repeats n − 1 times, but it only takes constant (O(1)) space, in contrast to the top-down approach which requires O(*n*) space to store the map.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] In both examples, we only calculate `fib(2)` one time, and then use it to calculate both `fib(4)` and `fib(3)`, instead of computing it every time either of them is evaluated.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Consider the problem of assigning values, either zero or one, to the positions of an *n* × *n* matrix, with *n* even, so that each row and each column contains exactly *n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] We ask how many different assignments there are for a given n.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] There are at least three possible approaches: brute force, backtracking, and dynamic programming.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Brute force consists of checking all assignments of zeros and ones and counting those that have balanced rows and columns (*n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] As there are $2^{n^{2}}$ possible assignments and ${\tbinom {n}{n/2}}^{n}$ sensible assignments, this strategy is not practical for arbitrarily large values of n .
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Backtracking for this problem consists of choosing some order of the matrix elements and recursively placing ones or zeros, while checking that in every row and column the number of elements that have not been assigned plus the number of ones or zeros are both at least *n* / 2.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] While more sophisticated than brute force, this approach will visit every solution once, making it impractical for *n* larger than six, since the number of solutions is already 116963796250 for *n* = 8, as we shall see.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming makes it possible to count the number of solutions without visiting them all.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Imagine backtracking values for the first row – what information would we require about the remaining rows, in order to be able to accurately count the solutions obtained for each first row value?
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] We consider *k* × *n* boards, where 1 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*, whose k rows contain $n/2$ zeros and $n/2$ ones.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The function *f* to which memoization is applied maps vectors of *n* pairs of integers to the number of admissible boards (solutions).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] There is one pair for each column, and its two components indicate respectively the number of zeros and ones that have yet to be placed in that column.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] If any one of the results is negative, then the assignment is invalid and does not contribute to the set of solutions (recursion stops).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Otherwise, we have an assignment for the top row of the *k* × *n* board and recursively compute the number of solutions to the remaining (*k* − 1) × *n* board, adding the numbers of solutions for every admissible assignment of the top row and returning the sum, which is being memoized.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The base case is the trivial subproblem, which occurs for a 1 × *n* board.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The number of solutions for this board is either zero or one, depending on whether the vector is a permutation of *n* / 2 (0, 1) and *n* / 2 (1, 0) pairs or not.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Links to the MAPLE implementation of the dynamic programming approach may be found among the external links.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Consider a checkerboard with *n* × *n* squares and a cost function `c(i, j)` which returns a cost associated with square `(i,j)` (`*i*` being the row, `*j*` being the column).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This problem exhibits **optimal substructure**.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] That is, the solution to the entire problem relies on solutions to subproblems.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Starting at rank `n` and descending to rank `1`, we compute the value of this function for all the squares at each successive rank.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Picking the square that holds the minimum value at each rank gives us the shortest path between rank `n` and rank `1`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The function `q(i, j)` is equal to the minimum cost to get to any of the three squares below it (since those are the only squares that can reach it) plus `c(i, j)`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The first line of this equation deals with a board modeled as squares indexed on `1` at the lowest bound and `n` at the highest bound.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The second line specifies what happens at the first rank; providing a base case.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The third line, the recursion, is the important part.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] It represents the `A,B,C,D` terms in the example.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] From this definition we can derive straightforward recursive code for `q(i, j)`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This function only computes the path cost, not the actual path.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This, like the Fibonacci-numbers example, is horribly slow because it too exhibits the **overlapping sub-problems** attribute.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] That is, it recomputes the same path costs over and over.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] However, we can compute it much faster in a bottom-up fashion if we store path costs in a two-dimensional array `q[i, j]` rather than using a function.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This avoids recomputation; all the values needed for array `q[i, j]` are computed ahead of time only once.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Precomputed values for `(i,j)` are simply looked up whenever needed.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] We also need to know what the actual shortest path is.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] To do this, we use another array `p[i, j]`; a *predecessor array*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This array records the path to any square `s`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The predecessor of `s` is modeled as an offset relative to the index (in `q[i, j]`) of the precomputed path cost of `s`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] To reconstruct the complete path, we lookup the predecessor of `s`, then the predecessor of that square, then the predecessor of that square, and so on recursively, until we reach the starting square.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Now the rest is a simple matter of finding the minimum and printing it.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] In genetics, sequence alignment is an important application where dynamic programming is essential.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Typically, the problem consists of transforming one sequence into another using edit operations that replace, insert, or remove an element.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Each operation has an associated cost, and the goal is to find the sequence of edits with the lowest total cost.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] 3. replacing the first character of A with the first character of B, and performing optimal alignments of the tails of A and B.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The partial alignments can be tabulated in a matrix, where cell (i,j) contains the cost of the optimal alignment of A[1..i] to B[1..j].
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The cost in cell (i,j) can be calculated by adding the cost of the relevant operations to the cost of its neighboring cells, and selecting the optimum.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Different variants exist, see Smith–Waterman algorithm and Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The **Tower of Hanoi** or **Towers of Hanoi** is a mathematical game or puzzle.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] It consists of three rods, and a number of disks of different sizes which can slide onto any rod.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The puzzle starts with the disks in a neat stack in ascending order of size on one rod, the smallest at the top, thus making a conical shape.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] S(n, h, t) := solution to a problem consisting of n disks that are to be moved from rod h to rod t.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] For n=1 the problem is trivial, namely S(1,h,t) = "move a disk from rod h to rod t" (there is only one disk left).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The number of moves required by this solution is 2*n* − 1.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] If the objective is to **maximize** the number of moves (without cycling) then the dynamic programming functional equation is slightly more complicated and 3*n* − 1 moves are required.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] A famous puzzle relates to dropping eggs from a building to determine at which height they start to break.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] terminology, in which the first floor is at ground level).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] If only one egg is available and we wish to be sure of obtaining the right result, the experiment can be carried out in only one way.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Drop the egg from the first-floor window; if it survives, drop it from the second-floor window.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] In the worst case, this method may require 36 droppings.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] What is the lowest number of egg-droppings that is guaranteed to work in all cases?
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] For instance, *s* = (2,6) indicates that two test eggs are available and 6 (consecutive) floors are yet to be tested.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The initial state of the process is *s* = (*N*,*H*) where *N* denotes the number of test eggs available at the commencement of the experiment.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The process terminates either when there are no more test eggs (*n* = 0) or when *k* = 0, whichever occurs first.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] If termination occurs at state *s* = (0,*k*) and *k* > 0, then the test failed.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] It is easy to solve this equation iteratively by systematically increasing the values of *n* and *k*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Notice that the above solution takes $O(nk^{2})$ time with a DP solution.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This can be improved to $O(nk\log k)$ time by binary searching on the optimal x in the above recurrence, since $W(n-1,x-1)$ is increasing in x while $W(n,k-x)$ is decreasing in x , thus a local minimum of $\max(W(n-1,x-1),W(n,k-x))$ is a global minimum.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Also, by storing the optimal x for each cell in the DP table and referring to its value for the previous cell, the optimal x for each cell can be found in constant time, improving it to $O(nk)$ time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Let k be the total number of floors such that the eggs break when dropped from the k th floor (The example above is equivalent to taking $k=37$ ).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Let m be the minimum floor from which the egg must be dropped to be broken.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Let $f(t,n)$ be the maximum number of values of m that are distinguishable using t tries and n eggs.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Let a be the floor from which the first egg is dropped in the optimal strategy.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] If the first egg broke, m is from 1 to a and distinguishable using at most $t-1$ tries and $n-1$ eggs.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] If the first egg did not break, m is from $a+1$ to k and distinguishable using $t-1$ tries and n eggs.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Then the problem is equivalent to finding the minimum x such that $f(x,n)\geq k$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] To do so, we could compute $\{f(t,i):0\leq i\leq n\}$ in order of increasing t , which would take $O(nx)$ time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Thus, if we separately handle the case of $n=1$ , the algorithm would take $O(n{\sqrt {k}})$ time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] But the recurrence relation can in fact be solved, giving $f(t,n)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}{\binom {t}{i}}$ , which can be computed in $O(n)$ time using the identity ${\binom {t}{i+1}}={\binom {t}{i}}{\frac {t-i}{i+1}}$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Since $f(t,n)\leq f(t+1,n)$ for all $t\geq 0$ , we can binary search on t to find x , giving an $O(n\log k)$ algorithm.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Matrix chain multiplication is a well-known example that demonstrates utility of dynamic programming.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] For example, engineering applications often have to multiply a chain of matrices.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] It is not surprising to find matrices of large dimensions, for example 100×100.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Matrix multiplication is not commutative, but is associative; and we can multiply only two matrices at a time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] There are numerous ways to multiply this chain of matrices.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] They will all produce the same final result, however they will take more or less time to compute, based on which particular matrices are multiplied.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] If matrix A has dimensions m×n and matrix B has dimensions n×q, then matrix C=A×B will have dimensions m×q, and will require m*n*q scalar multiplications (using a simplistic matrix multiplication algorithm for purposes of illustration).
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] For example, let us multiply matrices A, B and C.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Let us assume that their dimensions are m×n, n×p, and p×s, respectively.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] (A×B)×C This order of matrix multiplication will require mnp + mps scalar calculations.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] So, the first way to multiply the chain will require 1,000,000 + 1,000,000 calculations.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The second way will require only 10,000 + 100,000 calculations.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Obviously, the second way is faster, and we should multiply the matrices using that arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Therefore, our conclusion is that the order of parenthesis matters, and that our task is to find the optimal order of parenthesis.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] At this point, we have several choices, one of which is to design a dynamic programming algorithm that will split the problem into overlapping problems and calculate the optimal arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming solution is presented below.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Let's call m[i,j] the minimum number of scalar multiplications needed to multiply a chain of matrices from matrix i to matrix j (i.e.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] We split the chain at some matrix k, such that i <= k < j, and try to find out which combination produces minimum m[i,j].
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] So far, we have calculated values for all possible *m*[*i*, *j*], the minimum number of calculations to multiply a chain from matrix *i* to matrix *j*, and we have recorded the corresponding "split point"*s*[*i*, *j*].
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This algorithm will produce "tables" *m*[, ] and *s*[, ] that will have entries for all possible values of i and j.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The final solution for the entire chain is m[1, n], with corresponding split at s[1, n].
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Unraveling the solution will be recursive, starting from the top and continuing until we reach the base case, i.e. multiplication of single matrices.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Therefore, the next step is to actually split the chain, i.e. to place the parenthesis where they (optimally) belong.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Of course, this algorithm is not useful for actual multiplication.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This algorithm is just a user-friendly way to see what the result looks like.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The term *dynamic programming* was originally used in the 1940s by Richard Bellman to describe the process of solving problems where one needs to find the best decisions one after another.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] By 1953, he refined this to the modern meaning, referring specifically to nesting smaller decision problems inside larger decisions, and the field was thereafter recognized by the IEEE as a systems analysis and engineering topic.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Bellman's contribution is remembered in the name of the Bellman equation, a central result of dynamic programming which restates an optimization problem in recursive form.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The word *dynamic* was chosen by Bellman to capture the time-varying aspect of the problems, and because it sounded impressive.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The word *programming* referred to the use of the method to find an optimal *program*, in the sense of a military schedule for training or logistics.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] This usage is the same as that in the phrases *linear programming* and *mathematical programming*, a synonym for mathematical optimization.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] The above explanation of the origin of the term may be inaccurate: According to Russell and Norvig, the above story "cannot be strictly true, because his first paper using the term (Bellman, 1952) appeared before Wilson became Secretary of Defense in 1953." Also, Harold J.
[src:manacher-palindrome/dynamic-programming] Kushner stated in a speech that, "On the other hand, when I asked [Bellman] the same question, he replied that he was trying to upstage Dantzig's linear programming by adding dynamic.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] In computer science, a **longest common substring** of two or more strings is a longest string that is a substring of all of them.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] There may be more than one longest common substring.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Applications include data deduplication and plagiarism detection.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Unlike the longest common subsequence problem, which finds insertions or deletions within the common text, the longest common substring problem seeks a contiguous substring shared by both texts.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The picture shows two strings where the problem has multiple solutions.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Although the substring occurrences always overlap, it is impossible to obtain a longer common substring by "uniting" them.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The strings "ABABC", "BABCA" and "ABCBA" have only one longest common substring, viz.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Other common substrings are "A", "AB", "B", "BA", "BC" and "C".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Given two strings, S of length m and T of length n , find a longest string which is substring of both S and T .
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] A generalization is the *k*-**common substring problem**.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Find for each $2\leq k\leq K$ , a longest string which occurs as substring of at least k strings.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] One can find the lengths and starting positions of the longest common substrings of S and T in $\Theta$ $(n+m)$ time with the help of a generalized suffix tree.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] A faster algorithm can be achieved in the word RAM model of computation if the size $\sigma$ of the input alphabet is in $2^{o\left({\sqrt {\log(n+m)}}\right)}$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] In particular, this algorithm runs in ${\textstyle O\left((n+m)\log \sigma /{\sqrt {\log(n+m)}}\right)}$ time using $O\left((n+m)\log \sigma /\log(n+m)\right)$ space.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Solving the problem by dynamic programming costs $\Theta (nm)$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The solutions to the generalized problem take $\Theta (n_{1}+\cdots +n_{K})$ space and $\Theta (n_{1}\cdots n_{K})$ time with dynamic programming and take $\Theta (n_{1}+\cdots +n_{K})$ time with a generalized suffix tree.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The longest common substrings of a set of strings can be found by building a generalized suffix tree for the strings, and then finding the deepest internal nodes which have leaf nodes from all the strings in the subtree below it.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The figure on the right is the suffix tree for the strings "ABAB", "BABA" and "ABBA", padded with unique string terminators, to become "ABAB$0", "BABA$1" and "ABBA$2".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The nodes representing "A", "B", "AB" and "BA" all have descendant leaves from all of the strings, numbered 0, 1 and 2.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Building the suffix tree takes $\Theta (N)$ time (if the size of the alphabet is constant).
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] If the tree is traversed from the bottom up with a bit vector telling which strings are seen below each node, the k-common substring problem can be solved in $\Theta (NK)$ time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] If the suffix tree is prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval, it can be solved in $\Theta (N)$ time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The array `L` stores the length of the longest common suffix of the prefixes `S[1..i]` and `T[1..j]` which *end at position* `i` and `j`, respectively.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The variable `z` is used to hold the length of the longest common substring found so far.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The set `ret` is used to hold the set of strings which are of length `z`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] The set `ret` can be saved efficiently by just storing the index `i`, which is the last character of the longest common substring (of size z) instead of `S[(i-z+1)..i]`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-common-substring] Thus all the longest common substrings would be, for each i in `ret`, `S[(ret[i]-z)..(ret[i])]`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] In computer science, the **longest palindromic substring** or **longest symmetric factor** problem is the problem of finding a maximum-length contiguous substring of a given string that is also a palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] For example, the longest palindromic substring of "bananas" is "anana".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The longest palindromic substring is not guaranteed to be unique; for example, in the string "abracadabra", there is no palindromic substring with length greater than three, but there are two palindromic substrings with length three, namely, "aca" and "ada".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] In some applications it may be necessary to return all maximal palindromic substrings (that is, all substrings that are themselves palindromes and cannot be extended to larger palindromic substrings) rather than returning only one substring or returning the maximum length of a palindromic substring.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Manacher (1975) invented an $O(n)$ -time algorithm for listing all the palindromes that appear at the start of a given string of length n .
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] However, as observed e.g., by Apostolico, Breslauer & Galil (1995), the same algorithm can also be used to find all maximal palindromic substrings anywhere within the input string, again in $O(n)$ time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Therefore, it provides an $O(n)$ -time solution to the longest palindromic substring problem.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Alternative $O(n)$ -time solutions were provided by Jeuring (1994), and by Gusfield (1997), who described a solution based on suffix trees.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] A faster algorithm can be achieved in the word RAM model of computation if the size $\sigma$ of the input alphabet is in $2^{o(\log n)}$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] In particular, this algorithm runs in $O(n\log \sigma /\log n)$ time using $O(n\log \sigma /\log n)$ space.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Efficient parallel algorithms are also known for the problem.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The longest palindromic substring problem should not be confused with the different problem of finding the longest palindromic subsequence.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] This algorithm is slower than Manacher's algorithm, but is a good stepping stone for understanding Manacher's algorithm.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] It looks at each character as the center of a palindrome and loops to determine the largest palindrome with that center.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The loop at the center of the function only works for palindromes where the length is an odd number.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The function works for even-length palindromes by modifying the input string.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The character '|' is inserted between every character in the inputs string, and at both ends.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] So the input "book" becomes "|b|o|o|k|".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The even-length palindrome "oo" in "book" becomes the odd-length palindrome "|o|o|".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The runtime of this algorithm is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The outer loop runs n times and the inner loop can run up to $n/2$ times.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Below is the pseudocode for Manacher's algorithm.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The algorithm is faster than the previous algorithm because it exploits when a palindrome happens inside another palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] For example, consider the input string "abacaba".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] By the time it gets to the "c", Manacher's algorithm will have identified the length of every palindrome centered on the letters before the "c".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] At the "c", it runs a loop to identify the largest palindrome centered on the "c": "abacaba".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] With that knowledge, everything after the "c" looks like the reflection of everything before the "c".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The "a" after the "c" has the same longest palindrome as the "a" before the "c".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Similarly, the "b" after the "c" has a longest palindrome that is *at least* the length of the longest palindrome centered on the "b" before the "c".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] There are some special cases to consider, but that trick speeds up the computation dramatically.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Manacher's algorithm is faster because it reuses precomputed data when a palindrome exists inside another palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] They are represented by the "if / else if / else" statement in the pseudocode.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The first case is when the palindrome at `MirroredCenter` lies completely inside the "Old" palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] In this situation, the palindrome at `Center` will have the same length as the one at `MirroredCenter`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] For example, if the "Old" palindrome is "abcbpbcba", we can see that the palindrome centered on "c" after the "p" must have the same length as the palindrome centered on the "c" before the "p".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The second case is when the palindrome at `MirroredCenter` extends outside the "Old" palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] That is, it extends "to the left" (or, contains characters with a lower index than any inside the "Old" palindrome).
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Because the "Old" palindrome is the largest possible palindrome centered on `OldCenter`, we know the characters before and after it are different.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Thus, the palindrome at `Center` will run exactly up to the border of the "Old" palindrome, because the next character will be different than the one inside the palindrome at `MirroredCenter`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] For example, if the string was "ababc", the "Old" palindrome could be "bab" with the `Center` being the second "b" and the `MirroredCenter` being the first "b".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Since the palindrome at the `MirroredCenter` is "aba" and extends beyond the boundaries of the "Old" palindrome, we know the longest palindrome at the second "b" can only extend up to the border of the "Old" palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] We know this because if the character after the "Old" palindrome had been an "a" instead of a "c", the "Old" palindrome would have been longer.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The third and last case is when the palindrome at `MirroredCenter` extends exactly up to the border of the "Old" palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] In this case, we don't know if the character after the "Old" palindrome might make the palindrome at `Center` longer than the one at `MirroredCenter`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] But we do know that the palindrome at `Center` is *at least* as long as the one at `MirroredCenter`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] In this case, `Radius` is initialized to the radius of the palindrome at `MirroredCenter` and the search starts from there.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] An example string would be "abcbpbcbp" where the "Old" palindrome is "bcbpbcb" and the `Center` is on the second "c".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The `MirroredCenter` is the first "c" and it has a longest palindrome of "bcb".
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The longest palindrome at the `Center` on the second "c" has to be at least that long and, in this case, is longer.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] This can be seen by noting that `Center` strictly increases after each outer loop and the sum `Center + Radius` is non-decreasing.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Moreover, the number of operations in the first inner loop is linear in the increase of the sum `Center + Radius` while the number of operations in the second inner loop is linear in the increase of `Center`.
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] Since `Center ≤ 2n+1` and `Radius ≤ n`, the total number of operations in the first and second inner loops is $O(n)$ and the total number of operations in the outer loop, other than those in the inner loops, is also $O(n)$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/longest-palindromic-substring] The overall running time is therefore $O(n)$ .
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A **palindrome** (/ˈpælɪndroʊm/) is a word, number, phrase, or other sequence of symbols that reads the same backwards as forwards, such as *madam* or *racecar*, the date "22/02/2022", or the sentence "A man, a plan, a canal – Panama".
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The 19-letter Finnish word *saippuakivikauppias* (a soapstone vendor) is the longest single-word palindrome in everyday use, while the 12-letter term *tattarrattat* (from James Joyce in *Ulysses*) is the longest in English.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The word *palindrome* was introduced by English poet and writer Henry Peacham in 1638.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The concept of a palindrome can be dated to the 3rd-century BCE, although no examples survive.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Palindromes are also found in music (the table canon and crab canon) and biological structures (most genomes include palindromic gene sequences).
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In automata theory, the set of all palindromes over an alphabet is a context-free language, but it is not regular.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It is derived from the Greek roots *pálin* (πάλιν) 'again' and *drómos* (δρóμος) 'way, direction'; a different word is used in Greek, *karkinikós* (καρκινικός) 'carcinic' (lit.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] 'crab-like') to refer to letter-by-letter reversible writing.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The ancient Greek poet Sotades (3rd-century BCE) invented a form of Ionic meter called Sotadic or Sotadean verse, which is sometimes said to have been palindromic, since it is sometimes possible to make a sotadean line by reversing a dactylic hexameter.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A 1st-century Latin palindrome was found as a graffito at Pompeii.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] This palindrome, known as the Sator Square, consists of a sentence written in Latin: *sator arepo tenet opera rotas* 'The sower Arepo holds with effort the wheels'.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It is also an acrostic where the first letters of each word form the first word, the second letters form the second word, and so forth.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Hence, it can be arranged into a word square that reads in four different ways: horizontally or vertically from either top left to bottom right or bottom right to top left.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Other palindromes found at Pompeii include "Roma-Olim-Milo-Amor", which is also written as an acrostic square.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Indeed, composing palindromes was "a pastime of Roman landed gentry".
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The inscription is found on fonts in many churches in Western Europe: Orléans (St.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Menin's Abbey); Dulwich College; Nottingham (St.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Mary's); Worlingworth; Harlow; Knapton; London (St Martin, Ludgate); and Hadleigh (Suffolk).
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The palindromic Latin riddle "*In girum imus nocte et consumimur igni*" 'we go in a circle at night and are consumed by fire' describes the behavior of moths.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It is likely that this palindrome is from medieval rather than ancient times.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The second word, borrowed from Greek, should properly be spelled *gyrum*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] This is generally considered the first English-language palindrome sentence and was long reputed, notably by the grammarian James "Hermes" Harris, to be the *only* one, despite many efforts to find others.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] (Taylor had also composed two other, "rather indifferent", palindromic lines of poetry: "Deer Madam, Reed", "Deem if I meed".) Then in 1848, a certain "J.T.R." coined "Able was I ere I saw Elba", which became famous after it was (implausibly) attributed to Napoleon (alluding to his exile on Elba).
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Other well-known English palindromes are: "A man, a plan, a canal – Panama" (1948), "Madam, I'm Adam" (1861), and "Never odd or even" (1930).
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The most familiar palindromes in English are character-unit palindromes, where the characters read the same backward as forward.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Examples are *civic*, *radar*, *level*, *rotor*, *kayak*, *madam*, and *refer*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The longest common ones are *rotator, deified, racecar*, and *reviver*; longer examples such as *redivider*, *kinnikinnik*, and *tattarrattat* are orders of magnitude rarer.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] There are also word-unit palindromes in which the unit of reversal is the word ("Is it crazy how saying sentences backwards creates backwards sentences saying how crazy it is?").
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Word-unit palindromes were made popular in the recreational linguistics community by J.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Occasional examples in English were created in the 19th century.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Several in French and Latin date to the Middle Ages.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] There are also line-unit palindromes, most often poems.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] These possess an initial set of lines which, precisely halfway through, is repeated in reverse order, without alteration to word order within each line, and in a way that the second half continues the "story" related in the first half in a way that makes sense, this last being key.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Palindromes often consist of a sentence or phrase, e.g., "A man, a plan, a canal, Panama", "Mr.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Owl ate my metal worm", "Do geese see God?", or "Was it a car or a cat I saw?".
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Punctuation, capitalization, and spaces are usually ignored.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Some, such as "Rats live on no evil star", "Live on time, emit no evil", and "Step on no pets", include the spaces.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Some names are palindromes, such as the given names Hannah, Ava, Aviva, Anna, Eve, Bob, and Otto, or the surnames Harrah, Renner, Salas, and Nenonen.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Lon Nol (1913–1985) was Prime Minister of Cambodia.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Nisio Isin is a Japanese novelist and manga writer, whose pseudonym (西尾 維新, *Nishio Ishin*) is a palindrome when romanized using the Kunrei-shiki or the Nihon-shiki systems, and is often written as NisiOisiN to emphasize this.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Some people have changed their name in order to make it palindromic (including as the actor Robert Trebor and rock-vocalist Ola Salo), while others were given a palindromic name at birth (such as the philologist Revilo P.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Oliver, the flamenco dancer Sara Baras, the runner Anuța Cătună, the creator of the Eden Project Tim Smit, and the Mexican racing driver Noel León).
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] There are also palindromic names in fictional media.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] "Stanley Yelnats" is the name of the main character in *Holes*, a 1998 novel and 2003 film.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Five of the fictional *Pokémon* species have palindromic names in English (Eevee, Girafarig, Farigiraf, Ho-Oh, and Alomomola), as does the region Alola.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The 1970s pop band ABBA is a palindrome using the starting letter of the first name of each of the four band members.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The digits of a palindromic number are the same read backwards as forwards, for example, 91019; decimal representation is usually assumed.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In recreational mathematics, palindromic numbers with special properties are sought.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] For example, 191 and 313 are palindromic primes.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Whether Lychrel numbers exist is an unsolved problem in mathematics about whether all numbers become palindromes when they are continuously reversed and added.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] For example, 56 is not a Lychrel number as 56 + 65 = 121, and 121 is a palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Numbers such as 196 are thought to never become palindromes when this reversal process is carried out and are therefore suspected of being Lychrel numbers.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] If a number is not a Lychrel number, it is called a "delayed palindrome" (56 has a delay of 1 and 59 has a delay of 3).
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In January 2017 the number 1,999,291,987,030,606,810 was published in OEIS as A281509, and described as "The Largest Known Most Delayed Palindrome", with a delay of 261.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Several smaller 261-delay palindromes were published separately as A281508.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Every positive integer can be written as the sum of three palindromic numbers in every number system with base 5 or greater.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A day or timestamp is a palindrome when its digits are the same when reversed.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Only the digits are considered in this determination and the component separators (hyphens, slashes, and dots) are ignored.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Short digits may be used as in *11/11/11 11:11* or long digits as in *2 February 2020*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A notable palindrome day is this century's 2 February 2020 because this date is a palindrome regardless of the date format by country (yyyy-mm-dd, dd-mm-yyyy, or mm-dd-yyyy) used in various countries.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] For this reason, this date has also been termed as a "Universal Palindrome Day".
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A phonetic palindrome is a portion of speech that is identical or roughly identical when reversed.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It can arise in context where language is played with, for example in slang dialects like *verlan*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In the French language, there is the phrase *une Slave valse nue* ('a Slavic woman waltzes naked'), phonetically [yn slav vals ny].
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] John Oswald discussed his experience of phonetic palindromes while working on audio tape versions of the cut-up technique using recorded readings by William S.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A list of phonetic palindromes discussed by word puzzle columnist O.V.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Michaelsen (Ove Ofteness) include "crew work"/"work crew", "dry yard", "easy", "Funny enough", "Let Bob tell", "new moon", "selfless", "Sorry, Ross", "Talk, Scott", "to boot", "top spot" (also an orthographic palindrome), "Y'all lie", "You're caught.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The longest single-word palindrome in the *Oxford English Dictionary* is the 12-letter onomatopoeic word *tattarrattat*, coined by James Joyce in *Ulysses* (1922) for a knock on the door.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The *Guinness Book of Records* gives the title to the 11-letter *detartrated*, the preterite and past participle of *detartrate*, a chemical term meaning to remove tartrates.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The 9-letter word Rotavator, a trademarked name for an agricultural machine, is listed in dictionaries as being the longest single-word palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The 9-letter term *redivider* is used by some writers, but appears to be an invented or derived term; only *redivide* and *redivision* appear in the Shorter Oxford English Dictionary; the 9-letter word *Malayalam*, a language of southern India, is also of equal length.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] According to Guinness World Records, the Finnish 19-letter word *saippuakivikauppias* (a soapstone vendor), is the world's longest palindromic word in everyday use.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] English palindrome sentences of notable length include mathematician Peter Hilton's "Doc, note: I dissent.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] I diet on cod", and Scottish poet Alastair Reid's "T.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In English, two palindromic novels have been published: *Satire: Veritas* by David Stephens (1980, 58,795 letters), and *Dr Awkward & Olson in Oslo* by Lawrence Levine (1986, 31,954 words).
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Another palindromic English work is a 224-word long poem, "Dammit I'm Mad", written by Demetri Martin.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] "Weird Al" Yankovic's song "Bob" is composed entirely of palindromes.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In the third movement, a minuet and trio, the second half of the minuet is the same as the first but backwards, the second half of the ensuing trio similarly reflects the first half, and then the minuet is repeated.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The interlude from Alban Berg's opera *Lulu* is a palindrome, as are sections and pieces, in arch form, by many other composers, including James Tenney, and most famously Béla Bartók.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] George Crumb also used musical palindrome to text paint the Federico García Lorca poem "¿Por qué nací?", the first movement of three in his fourth book of Madrigals.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Igor Stravinsky's final composition, *The Owl and the Pussy Cat*, is a palindrome.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The first movement from Constant Lambert's ballet *Horoscope* (1938) is entitled "Palindromic Prelude".
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Lambert claimed that the theme was dictated to him by the ghost of Bernard van Dieren, who had died in 1936.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] British composer Robert Simpson also composed music in the palindrome or based on palindromic themes; the slow movement of his Symphony No.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] 2 is a palindrome, as is the slow movement of his String Quartet No.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] 9 consists of thirty-two variations and a fugue on a palindromic theme of Haydn (from the minuet of his Symphony No.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] All of Simpson's thirty-two variations are themselves palindromic.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The music of Anton Webern is often palindromic.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Webern, who had studied the music of the Renaissance composer Heinrich Isaac, was extremely interested in symmetries in music, be they horizontal or vertical.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] An example of horizontal or linear symmetry in Webern's music is the first phrase in the second movement of the symphony, Op.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A striking example of vertical symmetry is the second movement of the Piano Variations, Op.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] 27, in which Webern arranges every pitch of this dodecaphonic work around the central pitch axis of A4.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] From this, each downward reaching interval is replicated exactly in the opposite direction.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] For example, a G♯3—13 half-steps down from A4 is replicated as a B♭5—13 half-steps above.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Just as the letters of a verbal palindrome are not reversed, so are the elements of a musical palindrome usually presented in the same form in both halves.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Although these elements are usually single notes, palindromes may be made using more complex elements.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] For example, Karlheinz Stockhausen's composition *Mixtur*, originally written in 1964, consists of twenty sections, called "moments", which may be permuted in several different ways, including retrograde presentation, and two versions may be made in a single program.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] When the composer revised the work in 2003, he prescribed such a palindromic performance, with the twenty moments first played in a "forwards" version, and then "backwards".
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Each moment is a complex musical unit and is played in the same direction in each half of the program.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It is a perfect example of Goeyvaerts's aesthetics, the perfect example of the imperfection of perfection.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In classical music, a crab canon is a canon in which one line of the melody is reversed in time and pitch from the other.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A large-scale musical palindrome covering more than one movement is called "chiastic", referring to the cross-shaped Greek letter "χ" (pronounced /ˈkaɪ/.) This is usually a form of reference to the crucifixion; for example, the **Crucifixus** movement of Bach's Mass in B minor.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The purpose of such palindromic balancing is to focus the listener on the central movement, much as one would focus on the centre of the cross in the crucifixion.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Other examples are found in Bach's cantata BWV 4, *Christ lag in Todes Banden*, Handel's *Messiah* and Fauré's Requiem.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A table canon is a rectangular piece of sheet music intended to be played by two musicians facing each other across a table with the music between them, with one musician viewing the music upside down compared to the other.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The result is somewhat like two speakers simultaneously reading the Sator Square from opposite sides, except that it is typically in two-part polyphony rather than in unison.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Palindromic motifs are found in most genomes or sets of genetic instructions.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] The meaning of palindrome in the context of genetics is slightly different, from the definition used for words and sentences.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Since the DNA is formed by two paired strands of nucleotides, and the nucleotides always pair in the same way (Adenine (A) with Thymine (T), Cytosine (C) with Guanine (G)), a (single-stranded) sequence of DNA is said to be a palindrome if it is equal to its complementary sequence read backward.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] For example, the sequence ACCTAGGT is palindromic because its complement is TGGATCCA, which is equal to the original sequence in reverse complement.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A palindromic DNA sequence may form a hairpin.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Palindromic motifs are made by the order of the nucleotides that specify the complex chemicals (proteins) that, as a result of those genetic instructions, the cell is to produce.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] They have been specially researched in bacterial chromosomes and in the so-called Bacterial Interspersed Mosaic Elements (BIMEs) scattered over them.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In 2003, a research genome sequencing project discovered that many of the bases on the Y-chromosome are arranged as palindromes.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A palindrome structure allows the Y-chromosome to repair itself by bending over at the middle if one side is damaged.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It is believed that palindromes are also found in proteins, but their role in the protein function is not clearly known.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It has been suggested in 2008 that the prevalent existence of palindromes in peptides might be related to the prevalence of low-complexity regions in proteins, as palindromes frequently are associated with low-complexity sequences.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Their prevalence might also be related to an alpha helical formation propensity of these sequences, or in formation of protein/protein complexes.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In automata theory, a set of all palindromes in a given alphabet is a typical example of a language that is context-free, but not regular.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] This means that it is impossible for a finite automaton to reliably test for palindromes.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] In addition, the set of palindromes may not be reliably tested by a deterministic pushdown automaton which also means that they are not LR(k)-parsable or LL(k)-parsable.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] When reading a palindrome from left to right, it is, in essence, impossible to locate the "middle" until the entire word has been read completely.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] It is possible to find the longest palindromic substring of a given input string in linear time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] Among aperiodic words, the largest possible palindromic density is achieved by the Fibonacci word, which has density 1/φ, where φ is the Golden ratio.
[src:manacher-palindrome/palindrome] A **palstar** is a concatenation of palindromic strings, excluding the trivial one-letter palindromes – otherwise all strings would be palstars.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] In mathematics and computer science, a **string metric** (also known as a **string similarity metric** or **string distance function**) is a metric that measures distance ("inverse similarity") between two text strings for approximate string matching or comparison and in fuzzy string searching.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] A requirement for a string *metric* (e.g. in contrast to string matching) is fulfillment of the triangle inequality.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] For example, the strings "Sam" and "Samuel" can be considered to be close.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] A string metric provides a number indicating an algorithm-specific indication of distance.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] The most widely known string metric is a rudimentary one called the Levenshtein distance (also known as edit distance).
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] It operates between two input strings, returning a number equivalent to the number of substitutions and deletions needed in order to transform one input string into another.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] Simplistic string metrics such as Levenshtein distance have expanded to include phonetic, token, grammatical and character-based methods of statistical comparisons.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] There also exist functions which measure a dissimilarity between strings, but do not necessarily fulfill the triangle inequality, and as such are not *metrics* in the mathematical sense.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-metric] An example of such function is the Jaro–Winkler distance.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] A **string-searching algorithm**, sometimes called **string-matching algorithm**, is an algorithm that searches a body of text for portions that match by pattern.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In practice, the method of feasible string-search algorithm may be affected by the string encoding.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In particular, if a variable-width encoding is in use, then it may be slower to find the *N*th character, perhaps requiring time proportional to *N*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] This may significantly slow some search algorithms.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] One of many possible solutions is to search for the sequence of code units instead, but doing so may produce false matches unless the encoding is specifically designed to avoid it.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] The most basic case of string searching involves one (often very long) string, sometimes called the *haystack*, and one (often very short) string, sometimes called the *needle*.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] The goal is to find one or more occurrences of the needle within the haystack.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] One might request the first occurrence of "to", which is the fourth word; or all occurrences, of which there are 3; or the last, which is the fifth word from the end.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Very commonly, however, various constraints are added.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might want to match the "needle" only where it consists of one (or more) complete words—perhaps defined as *not* having other letters immediately adjacent on either side.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In that case a search for "hew" or "low" should fail for the example sentence above, even though those literal strings do occur.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Another common example involves "normalization".
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Finally, for strings that represent natural language, aspects of the language itself become involved.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might wish to find all occurrences of a "word" despite it having alternate spellings, prefixes or suffixes, etc.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Another more complex type of search is regular expression searching, where the user constructs a pattern of characters or other symbols, and any match to the pattern should fulfill the search.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] where the "?" conventionally makes the preceding character ("u") optional.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] This article mainly discusses algorithms for the simpler kinds of string searching.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] A similar problem introduced in the field of bioinformatics and genomics is the maximal exact matching (MEM).
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Given two strings, MEMs are common substrings that cannot be extended left or right without causing a mismatch.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] A simple and inefficient way to see where one string occurs inside another is to check at each index, one by one.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] First, we see if there is a copy of the needle starting at the first character of the haystack; if not, we look to see if there's a copy of the needle starting at the second character of the haystack, and so forth.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In this approach, backtracking is avoided by constructing a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that recognizes a stored search string.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] These are expensive to construct—they are usually created using the powerset construction—but are very quick to use.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] For example, the DFA shown to the right recognizes the word "MOMMY".
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] This approach is frequently generalized in practice to search for arbitrary regular expressions.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Knuth–Morris–Pratt computes a DFA that recognizes inputs with the string to search for as a suffix, Boyer–Moore starts searching from the end of the needle, so it can usually jump ahead a whole needle-length at each step.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Baeza–Yates keeps track of whether the previous *j* characters were a prefix of the search string, and is therefore adaptable to fuzzy string searching.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] The bitap algorithm is an application of Baeza–Yates' approach.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Faster search algorithms preprocess the text.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] After building a substring index, for example a suffix tree or suffix array, the occurrences of a pattern can be found quickly.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] As an example, a suffix tree can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, and all z occurrences of a pattern can be found in $O(m)$ time under the assumption that the alphabet has a constant size and all inner nodes in the suffix tree know what leaves are underneath them.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] The latter can be accomplished by running a DFS algorithm from the root of the suffix tree.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Some search methods, for instance trigram search, are intended to find a "closeness" score between the search string and the text rather than a "match/non-match".
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] These are sometimes called "fuzzy" searches.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] The various algorithms can be classified by the number of patterns each uses.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *m* is the length of the pattern, *n* the length of the searchable text, and *k* = |Σ| is the size of the alphabet.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] The **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** has been the standard benchmark for the practical string-search literature.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *M* is the length of the longest pattern, *m* their total length, *n* the length of the searchable text, *o* the number of occurrences.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Naturally, the patterns can not be enumerated finitely in this case.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] They are represented usually by a regular grammar or regular expression.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Other classification approaches are possible.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] One of the most common uses preprocessing as main criteria.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In real-time string matching, one requires the matcher to output a response after reading each character of the text, that indicates whether this is the last character of a match.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] The response has to be given within constant time.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] For the more lenient version, if one does not mind that the preprocessing time and memory requirement dependend on the size of the alphabet, a real-time solution is provided by automaton matching.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Zvi Galil developed a method to turn certain algorithms into real-time algorithms, and applied it to produce a variant of the KMP matcher that runs in real time under the strict requirement.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In this version of the string searching problem, there is a special symbol, ø (read: don't care), which can match any other symbol (including another ø).
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Don't care symbols can appear either in the pattern or in the text.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] In 2002, an algorithm for this problem that runs in $O(n\log m)$ time has been given by Richard Cole and Ramesh Hariharan, improving on a solution from 1973 by Fischer and Paterson that has complexity $O(n\log m\log k)$ , where *k* is the size of the alphabet.
[src:manacher-palindrome/string-searching-algorithm] Another algorithm, claimed simpler, has been proposed by Clifford and Clifford.
